Now we observe residuals: Residuals do not look like a white noise. Also we can see that there is still some autocorrelated residuals left. So it might be the case, that ETS model did not capture all of the structure of data. Ljung-Box test p-values for them:

Hypothesis Test Result P-value
Normality Shapiro-Wilk not rejected 0.6316342
Unbiasedness Wilcoxon not rejected 0.7670181
Stationarity KPSS not rejected 0.1

OK, residuals are normal, unbiased and stationary. This is good.

### Manual model tuning The series are seasonal, so we want to perform seasonal differencing.

Let’s see if regular differencing makes it more better.

The hypothesis of stationarity is not rejected (p>0.1, KPSS test). Autocorrelation is significantly different from 0 for lags 1, 12, 13, 41, 53 Since 12 is maximal significant seasonal lag, we could use \(Q = 12/12 = 1\) as an initial approximation. Maximal significant lag before 12 is 1, hence the starting value \(q=1\).

Partial autocorrelation is significantly different from 0 for lags 1, 4, 7, 12, 24, 41 Following the same logic as above, we select initial values \(P=2\), \(p=7\).

Now I’ll look for the best models with auto.arima using d=1, D=1, max.p=8, max.q=2, max.P=3, max.Q=2 (where possible, I added 1 to every initial approximation found above just in case), and the parameters of the automatic model as starting points of the search (start.p=1, start.q=0, start.P=0, start.Q=0).

## Final model selection

Comparing the residuals of two ARIMAs: Residuals are different from auto ARIMA and manually tuned ARIMA.

Auto ARIMA vs Manual

## 
##  Diebold-Mariano Test
## 
## data:  resres.auto
## DM = 1.8906, Forecast horizon = 1, Loss function power = 2, p-value =
## 0.0618
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided

We cannot reject that there is no significant difference in forecasting error between auto ARIMA and manual ARIMA. Based on AICc score and losses on test set and Theil’s U it should be safe to prefer auto ARIMA over manual ARIMA.

Now let’s compare it to ets model Comparing the residuals of the best ARIMA and the best ETS models:

Their residuals are also different.

## DM = -0.28918, Forecast horizon = 1, Loss function power = 2, p-value =
## 0.6135
## alternative hypothesis: greater

Diebold-Mariano Test shows no significant evidence to reject the null that their forecasts are different. * Auto ARIMA had the lowest AICc score (593). Their losses on test set are fluctiuating, so it is hard to determine which model is better on a test set. Its Theil’s U is 0.23 * ETS model has the highest AICc (861) score, but its Theil’s U is smaller (0.21).

For this hard decision, I decide to use auto ARIMA model based on AICc.
